"ogimage":"http://s3-media1.ak.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/j61EBKmMyBJTBJvzAVXw1w/l.jpg",
"rating":"4.5",
"reviewcomment":"My Holy Grail.  Truly a 3-star Michelin Experience.<br><br>Through the help of my boyfriend&#39;s friend who works at Per Se, we were fortunate enough to have reservations for lunch this past Sunday and boy was it a memorable experience!  We were seated without a doubt at the best table in the dining room, right next to the main window overlooking Columbus Circle and Central Park.  The view was breathtaking!<br><br>We were promptly offered some delicious French Champagne and then greeted by our server (who btw was dressed in a very nice suit) and told that we had a choice between three different tastings: a 5 course, a 7 course and a 10 course Chef&#39;s tasting.  Since there really isn&#39;t too many opportunities for either of us to dine at Per Se since we both don&#39;t live in NYC, we decided the 10 course was the only way to go.  Our meal totaled to 13 Courses not including the amuse bouche, thanks to a few courses complimented by the kitchen :)  Our meal went as follows:<br><br>1. Savory Profiteroles: Yummy melted gruyere cheese puff.  light and savory<br><br>2. Smoked Salmon Cone: A Thomas Keller Classic.  Smoked Salmon with creme fraiche inside a light savory cone.  I do not enjoy eating raw fish or smoked fish, but this was delightful.  The salmon and the creme fraiche worked very well together and the crispy wafer-like sesame? cone was delicious.<br><br>3.  Forest Mushroom Soup: I loooooveee mushrooms, and this soup was like pure mushroom and cream puree.  It was so so good.  And the serving size was like a full sized portion of soup.  <br><br>4.  &#34;Oysters and Pearls&#34;:  The signature.  I was really tempted to opt out of oyster items and caviar items when we were asked to mention any food-items we did not care for in the reservation, but I&#39;m so glad I took a risk. The presentation was beautiful, with two oysters sitting atop of tapioca and this wonderfully creamy looking sauce, right next to the oysters was a canelle of sterling white sturgeon caviar.  All of the food items I do not wish to eat on a plate.  Mind blown.  This dish was amazing.  The oysters were almost sweet and combined with the tapioca, cream sauce and caviar, the flavor was just phenomenal.  Can not recommend this dish enough.<br><br>5.  White Truffle Infused Custard: This was served inside a cracked egg shell.  Decadent with more black truffle sauce topping the white truffle egg custard.  I could eat a whole flat&#39;s worth of these custard eggs. (There are 36 eggs in a flat).<br><br>6.  Cauliflower Salad: After several extremely rich and creamy courses, this was a welcoming palate cleanser.  Fresh, with notes of citrus and aged balsamic vinegar.<br><br>Bread intermission: Sourdough, multi-grain and Baguette.  Served with two types of butter.  One butter from Vermont (unsalted) and the other salted from California.<br><br>7. Atlantic Monk fish: This I was told, was a full filet of Monk fish served on top of lentils and pearl onions.  I&#39;ve never had monk fish before and I can tell you it was an interesting experience.  The texture is extremely firm for a fish, and the flavor is mild like a white fish.  It wasn&#39;t my favorite, but tasty for something I&#39;ve never had before.<br><br>8. Brussels Sprout Encrusted Main Sea Scallops: These were just melt in your mouth.  Definitely the best scallop preparation I&#39;ve ever had.  These were served with applewood bacon, brussels sprouts over a brown butter sauce.  <br><br>9. Cuisse De Poularde: This was a slice of I believe chicken thigh stuffed with mousse and served atop a curry sauce and dates.  A very middle-eastern/ India inspired dish.  The flavors were unlike any of the previous dishes we had tasted and provided a nice contrast from the courses before.<br><br>10.  Elysian Field&#39;s Lamb: Okay.  This is where I am a little confused as I had specifically requested no lamb, yet I was served lamb.. Oops? Haha.  I do not like the gaminess of lamb, but the lamb served at Per Se was probably the least gamey with very little gamey taste at all.  Honestly if it didn&#39;t look like a rack of lamb, I wouldn&#39;t have even known.  The meat was very tender and well executed with artichokes and ricotta gnocchi.<br><br>11.  Cheese Course: The cheese was raw sheep cheese served with a homemade sour cherry newton and roasted nuts.  Delicious.<br><br>12. Tropical Fruit Cup: Pineapple cubes, Passionfruit puree and White tea foam.  The white tea was bitter but worked moderately well with the tropical fruits.  I think this dish would have been better had the fruits been even sweeter and less sour.<br><br>13. Okinawan Brown Sugar Ice Cream: Delicious (got to cut this review short running out of review space lol)<br><br>14. Maralumi Chocolate: Like a home made Aero Bar, with genoise cake and marshmallow topping<br><br>15. Assorted Chocolates, Nougats and Macarons. <br><br>Toured the kitchen and found out it was the 10th Anniversary of Per Se.  Left full, happy, and with a goody bag filled with chocolates, cookies and a French Laundry Cookbook signed by Thomas Keller(courtesy of the bf).  I&#39;m so spoiled.",
